<DOC><DOCNO> AP880513-0279 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1515EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     05-13 0295</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0310</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The stock market showed a broad gain today,inspired by falling interest rates and a steady dollar in foreignexchange.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 16.42 to 1,984.42by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in the overalltally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 1,013 up, 427down and 500 unchanged.   As the dollar strengthened against leading foreign currencies,prices of long-term government bonds rose as much as $5 for each$1,000 in face value in the credit markets.   Analysts said investors around the world were encouraged by thesuccessful completion late Thursday of the Treasury's three-dayauction of $26 billion in bonds and notes.   Brokers also noted that there were no unpleasant surprises inthe Labor Department's report this morning that the producer priceindex of finished goods rose 0.4 percent last month.   In addition, Japan reported a continued narrowing of itsinternational trade surplus. The Commerce Department is due toreport next week on the latest monthly U.S. trade balance.   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up 1 at 45; GeneralElectric, up ] at 39]; International Business Machines, up 1[ at109~, and Ford Motor, up | at 47~.   Niagara Mohawk Power led the active list, up [ at 14| onturnover of more than 25 million shares. Most of the activity inthe stock was attributed to strategies aimed at the company'simpending quarterly dividend.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocksclimbed 1.21 to 144.99. At the American Stock Exchange, the marketvalue index was up .83 at 297.44.   Volume on the Big Board came to 127.10 million shares with anhour to go.</TEXT></DOC>